Fund Overview

An Australian first, this HealthTech venture capital fund has been established to identify and invest via equity crowdfunding in early stage companies innovating in the areas of health and wellness. The fund will find and fund high-growth ventures in the areas of FoodTech, MedTech, BioTech & Digital Health.

The fund is targeting a 25%+ IRR over its life and is structured as an Early Stage Venture Capital Limited Partnership* giving investors a 10% tax offset and tax-free returns.

Investors will gain passive exposure to a diversified portfolio of companies innovating in the fast growing HealthTech sector as well as having first access to increase their exposure to particular companies through the VentureCrowd platform as the companies gain traction.

The highlights of the opportunity are as follows:

  • High growth health & wellness sector
  • Exclusive early access to LuminaX HealthTech Accelerator companies
  • Managed by VentureCrowd funds management
  • Experienced investment team & investment committee
  • Strong track record of HealthTech investments
  • 10% tax offset plus tax-free returns
  • Targeting first exits within 3-5 years
  • Targeting 25%+ IRR

* Pending registration

What is HealthTech?

HealthTech refers to innovative technologies that have the potential to make a positive impact on health and wellness generally, and includes sub sectors such as FoodTech, MedTech, BioTech & Digital Health companies.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
FoodTech

FoodTech is the convergence of technology with the food and agriculture sector to reshape the future of food, from the farm to the plate. The next generation of food companies will elevate health, wellness and sustainability as key priorities in response to rising consumer demand.

Generally, FoodTech companies fall into one of the following categories:

  • Production
  • Distribution
  • Consumption
  • Waste Management

The increasing focus from consumers on nutrition, health and sustainability, and the failure of industry incumbents to adequately address those needs, is driving a rapid rise in FoodTech innovation, with startups filling the gaps left by incumbents.

In 2020, global FoodTech startups raised an estimated USD 26 billion, which represents a 35% increase on the year before. The COVID-19 pandemic has further increased investment across all segments, with no signs of slowing. In fact, the global FoodTech market is currently forecast to grow to USD 346 billion by 2027 at a CAGR of 6.0%.

Itâ€™s clear that FoodTech is no longer an early-stage industry but very much a new growth sector and one investors should watch closely. Read more about FoodTech in VentureCrowdâ€™s white paper The Future of Food.

VentureCrowd FoodTech Success Story:

Through VentureCrowd, Nexba raised $6M in a Series A round at a pre-money valuation of $20M including a syndicate of VentureCrowd members. In FY17 the company had gross revenue of $2.5M with VentureCrowd investors investing at a pre-money valuation of $20M. Since then, VentureCrowd has raised 2 additional rounds of capital for Nexba. In FY21 the company had grown to $35M gross revenue and is forecast to nearly double again in FY22.

componentInstanceProperties.value:
BioTech

BioTech is short for biotechnology and refers to technology that utilises biological systems and living organisms to develop technological advances which can be adapted to various fields from agricultural practice to the medical sector.

It includes things like new drugs, vaccines, antibiotics, gene therapy, molecular diagnosis and everything from biofuels to pest resistant crops.

According to McKinsey, between 2019 and 2020, BioTech saw double-digit annual growth in fundraising from VCs and deals such as partnerships, and joint ventures. It also saw triple-digit growth in IPOs.

Between January 2020 and January 2021, the average share price for European and US BioTechs increased at more than twice the rate of the S&P 500, and Chinese BioTechs performed more than six times better, with their average share price more than doubling in a year.

Overall, BioTech is outperforming the pharmaceutical industry, as well as many household-name consumer-goods and technology companies.

Australia is considered to be among the top 5 countries for biotechnology in the world ahead of countries like the United Kingdom and Germany and has been responsible for some of the worldâ€™s leading BioTech innovations such as the Cochlear implant and the cervical cancer vaccine.

The VentureCrowd team believes Australia remains well placed to continue to be a global leader in BioTech into the future.

VentureCrowd BioTech Success Story:

BioTech portfolio companies includes companies like EngeneIC, a Sydney-based company with a proprietary EDVâ„¢ (EnGeneIC Deam Vector) nanocell platform enabling the targeted delivery of chemotherapeutics and functional nucleic acids in cancer treatment. EnGeneICâ€™s original target was to raise $1 million in capital via equity crowdfunding in a pre-IPO round ahead of its listing on the NASDAQ in Q2 2022. EnGeneIC ended up raising $5 million in total, which exceeded its target by 500% or $4 million.

MedTech

Medtech is short for medical technology and refers to technology driven products, services or solutions used in the diagnosis, prevention, treatment and management of disease and disability.

It includes a diverse range of products from syringes and wound dressings, to implantable devices such as pacemakers, defibrillators, bone and joint replacements, and other prostheses, and hospital and diagnostic imaging equipment such as ultrasound and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) equipment.

The global MedTech industry has contributed to a 30% decline in annual mortality in the last 20 years, an 18.7% decline in disability rates in the last 15 years, a 56% reduction in hospital bed days and an increase in life expectancy by 4.1 years.

Australiaâ€™s MedTech industry is one of the most dynamic advanced manufacturing sectors in Australia and has consistently produced world-class medical device companies exporting Australian innovation to the world, including Prism Surgical, Cochlear Australia and ResMed.

The total market for medical devices in Australia is valued at over US$4.9 billion and is ranked 13th in the world in terms of total market value.

The Australian Bureau of Statistics identified the industry as a growth industry, performing higher than average on indicators such as export, productivity and employment.

Digital Health

Digital health refers to the use of information and communications technologies in medicine and allied health to promote wellness and to prevent and manage physical and mental illness and health risks.

Digital health technologies include both hardware and software solutions and services, including telemedicine, wearable devices, augmented reality, and virtual reality. Generally, digital health interconnects health systems to improve the use of computational technologies, smart devices, computational analysis techniques, and communication media to aid healthcare professionals and their patients manage illnesses and health risks, as well as promote health and wellbeing.

As technology continues to democratise access to healthcare, it is also enabling a change in mindset that places greater focus on a healthier lifestyle rather than on the current emphasis on treatment and aftercare. This puts the consumer at the centre of innovation, broadening the meaning of health to physical, social, financial, spiritual, emotional and mental wellness.

Forecasts indicate the global digital health market will continue to grow at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of over 15% p.a. to reach USD 258 billion by 2028.

This space will continue to be catalysed by the global consumer need for hyper-convenience and personalisation, driving the need to improve healthcare accessibility, quality and safety through technology.

VentureCrowd MedTech Success Stories:

Cardihab was VentureCrowdâ€™s first Digital Health Investment. Their online rehabilitation platform supports cardiac patients in recovery and reduces hospital re-admissions. The company is helping patients reach optimal health when at risk of, or living with, heart disease - globally. They're by a strong commercial Board and Management. Notable shareholders include Artesian Capital Management, StoicVC and QCG.

Fund Structure

The Fund is structured as an Early Stage Venture Capital Limited Partnership (ESVCLP) pending registration with Industry, Innovation & Science Australia. Investors will acquire limited partnership interests in the Fund which will be governed by the Partnership Deed.

componentInstanceProperties.name: richTextValue
componentInstanceProperties.value:
Tax Concessions

The ESVCLP program is a federal government initiative designed to stimulate investment into Australiaâ€™s early stage venture capital sector by allowing generous tax concessions to investors of funds that meet certain criteria.

A fund registered as an ESVCLP will have flow-through tax treatment and will not be taxed at the partnership level. Generally, the following tax concessions are available:

  • Non-refundable carry-forward tax offset of up to 10% on contributions made at any time to an ESVCLP that becomes unconditionally registered.
  • Capital gains or profits from the disposal or realisation of an investment by the Fund, operating as an ESVCLP, are exempt from Australian income tax if the Fund owned the investment for at least 12 months.
  • Income derived from an investment of the Fund (such as dividends paid by an Investee Company) is exempt from Australian income tax.
  • Losses from the disposal or realisation of investments by the Fund are not deductible for Australian income tax purposes.

Investors should seek their own advice regarding the tax implications of investing in the Fund, including the tax treatment of income received as a result of the investment, in overseas territories (as applicable).

Fund Risk Warning

Investing in private companies and venture capital funds is risky. The fund manager will be investing in new or rapidly growing ventures. Investment in these types of ventures is speculative and carries high risks.

You may lose your entire investment, and you should be in a position to bear this risk without undue hardship. Even if the fundâ€™s investment in a company is successful, the value of its investment and any return on the investment could be reduced if the company issues more shares.

Investments made by the fund are unlikely to be liquid. This means the fund is unlikely to be able to sell its shares quickly or on a convenient date. Even though the fund may have remedies for misleading statements in an offer document or misconduct by investee companies, it may have difficulty recovering money invested.

Ask questions, read all information given carefully, and seek independent financial advice before committing yourself to any investment.
